Nutrition










1. MODE OF NUTRITION

Nutrition can be mainly divided into two, namely, Autotrophic and Heterotrophic Nutrition.

1.     Autotrophic Nutrition

This is a form of nutrition whereby organisms produce their own food from simple inorganic substances. They are further sub-divided into two (2) namely;

a.     Photosynthesis: Some green plants synthesize sugar from water and carbon dioxide because of the presence of chlorophyll and adequate sunlight.

b.     Chemosynthesis: some bacteria which produce their food from water, carbon dioxide and hydrogen sulphide use the energy emitted during chemical reactions.

2.     Heterotopic Nutrition

It is a form of nutrition whereby organisms feed on organic substance produced by other organisms i.e. autotrophic organisms. Examples of heterotrophs are animals, fungi, some species of bacteria etc. it is sub-divided into five;

a.     Holozoic Nutrition: This occurs when organisms ingest complex organic molecules that need proper digestion before it becomes useful in the body. His form of nutrition can be found in herbivores e.g. Goat, sheep, carnivores e.g. Lion, tiger and omnivores e.g. man, etc.

b.     Parasitic Nutrition: It occurs when organisms known as parasites derive their nutrients from other organisms known as the hosts. The parasites which live in the host are known as endoparasites while those living on the hosts are ectoparasites e.g. Ticks, fleas, etc. while examples of endoparasites are tapeworm, plasmodium etc.

c.     Saprophytic Nutrition:It is a form of nutrition whereby the organism feeds on decaying and dead matter. Saprophytes secrete enzymes onto the decaying begins and digestion occurs extracellularly. Examples of saprophytes are bacteria and fungi.

d.     Symbiotic Nutrition: This is an association with organisms of different species in which both benefit nutritionally. E.g. the bacterium, trichonympha aids the digestion of cellulose in the alimentary canal of termite and in return gets nourishment and shelter from termite.

e.     Carnivorous Nutrition in Plants: This occurs when some green plants supplement their nutrition requirement by catching and digesting insects e.g. bladderwort, sundew, venus, flytrap.


2. NUTRITION: PLANT NUTRITION

By the term 'plant', we mean any organism that is capable of self-production of food using energy derived from an external source.

Generally, plants are autotrophs (independent producers of food). They have structures that are adapted to trap the necessary materials needed to produce their food.

Autotrophs include;

1.     Phototrophs (Autotrophs that use the sunlight energy to manufacture their food), e.g. algae, bryophytes, seed plants, etc.

2.     Chemotrophs (Autotrophs that use chemical energy gotten by oxidation to manufacture their food) e.g. bacteria like cyanobacteria, green and purple sulphur bacteria.

Phototrophic Autotrophic Mode of Nutrition

Autotrophs that manufacture their food by phototrophic means carry out photosynthesis.

Photosynthesis

This is the anabolic process through which green plants manufacture their food using carbon dioxide and water in the presence of chlorophyll and sunlight giving out oxygen as a by-product.

Chlorophyll

The process of photosynthesis is represented in the equation below;

Sunlight

6CO2 + 6H2O           C6H12O6 + 6O2

Stages of Photosynthesis

There are two stages involved in photosynthesis; they include;

1.     Light reaction stage

2.     Dark reaction stage

Leaf A Photosynthetic Organ

The leaf is the site at which photosynthesis takes place in a green plant. The green leaf contains chlorophyll which helps to trap the sunlight energy; the leaf blade enables a wide surface which makes the sunlight to reach every part of the leaf; the leaf stalk holds the leaf in position so that it will receive maximum sunlight; the thinness of the leaf enables short distance for carbon dioxide to diffuse into leaf cells; the stomata in the leaf allows CO2to diffuse in and O2 to diffuse out of the leaf, the leaf has veins containing xylem for water and mineral salt conduction to mesophyll cells; and phloem for sugar conduction away from the leaf.


Conditions Necessary for Photosynthesis

The following conditions are necessary for photosynthesis to take place;

1.     Carbon dioxide

This is a necessary raw material which is absorbed by the stomata of leaves from the atmosphere.

2.     Water

This is also an important raw material which is absorbed by the root from the soil and conducted to the leaf.

3.     Chlorophyll

This pigment (green) is found in the chloroplast in the leaf. It is the pigment needed to trap the sunlight energy which will activate the anabolic chemical reaction between carbon dioxide and water.

4.     Sunlight

This is the energy source for the process of photosynthesis.

Importance of Photosynthesis

The importance of photosynthesis include;

1.     Supply of food by plants to heterotrophs (consumers)

2.     Release of oxygen to the atmosphere for respiration

3.     Reduction of the carbon dioxide content of the atmosphere thereby reducing global warming.

4.     Supply of energy (which are stored in the food manufactured)

Mineral Requirement of Plants

·     Minerals are inorganic elements formed as a result of weathering of rocks into soil.

·     Weathering is the mechanical or chemical breaking down of rocks to form soil.

·     Depending on the quantities required by plants, minerals are classified as;

1.     Micro/Trace Elements

2.     Macro/Major Elements

Micro Elements

These elements are required in small, quantities by the plant. They include;

·     Manganese

·     Copper

·     Boron

·     Zinc

·     Cobalt

·     Chlorine

·     Molybdenum

Macro Elements

These elements are required in large quantities by the plants for proper growth and development. They include

·     Phosphorus

·     Magnesium

·     Iron

·     Hydrogen

·     Sulphur

·     Nitrogen

·     Calcium

·     Oxygen

·     Potassium


3. ANIMAL NUTRITION AND FOOD CLASSES

By the term 'Animal' we mean any organism that is not capable of self-production but depends directly or in-directly on plants for its food.

Animals are referred to as heterotrophs

Food Classes

The foods taken by animals are composed of nutrients. These nutrients may include;

1.     Carbohydrate

2.     Proteins

3.     Fats/Oils

4.     Mineral salts

5.     Vitamins

6.     Water

1.     Carbohydrate

·     Constituent elements: Carbon, Hydrogen, Oxygen

·     Importance: It is an energy giving food

·     Food sources: cassava, rice, yam, potato.

2.     Proteins

·     Constituent elements: carbon, hydrogen, oxygen and nitrogen

·     Importance: i. It is used for the repair of worn out tissues

ii. It is used for the formation of enzymes and hormones

iii. It helps in the growth and development of the body (body building)

·     Food sources: cowpea, fish, groundnuts, soya, etc.

3.     Fats / Oils

·     Constituent elements: carbon, hydrogen, oxygen

·     Importance: i. It is an energy giving food (it gives more energy than carbohydrates

ii. It helps to insulate the body: hence reducing heat loss to surrounding

iii. It aids the formulation of cell membranes

·     Food sources: Margarine, butter, egg, yolk, palm oil, cheese etc.

4.     Mineral Salts

·     Constituent elements: potassium, calcium, sulphur, magnesium, sodium, chlorine, iron, copper, manganese, iodine, zinc, fluorine

·     Importance: i. They are required for building string bones and teeth

ii. They aid blood formation

iii. They are required for the proper growth and development of thebody

iv. They are needed for maintaining normal health

·     Food sources: vegetables, cheese, liver, onion

5.     Vitamins

·     Constituent elements: Carbon, Hydrogen, Oxygen,Phosphorus

·     Importance:     i. They act as biocatalyst i.e. they promote chemical reactions in the body

ii.They help to prevent diseases

·     Food sources: vegetables, fruits, egg, yolk, etc.

6.     Water

·     Constituent elements: hydrogen and oxygen

·     Importance: i. It acts as a transporting agent

ii. It is needed for hydrolytic reactions (digestion)

iii. It acts as a raw material in the process of photosynthesis

iv. It helps to regulate body temperature

·     Food sources: water from food substances, Tap water, ionized water etc.

Roughage (Dietary Fibre)

Roughage also known as fibre or bulk are indigestible compounds that the body cannot absorb.

It is found mainly in fruits, vegetables, grains and legumes. A high fibre diet has many advantages including bowel regularity (preventing constipation) and decreased risk of high blood pressure, diverticulus and diabetes.

N.B: Constipation is a condition of the bowels in which the faeces are dry and hardened and evacuation is difficult and infrequent.

Constipation is prevented by drinking enough fluids, eating more fibre and exercise.

BALANCED DIET

·     Diet

This is the sum of food consumed by a person or the other organisms.

·     Balanced diet

A diet is said to be balanced if it contains the proper proportions of carbohydrates, fats, proteins, vitamins, minerals and water necessary to maintain good health.

Nutritional Deficiency

A nutritional deficiency occurs when the body does not absorb or get from food the necessary amount of a particular nutrient.

Some nutritional deficiency includes:

1.     Kwashiorkor à Protein deficiency

2.     Goitre à Iodine deficiency

3.     Scurvy à Vitamin C deficiency

4.     Night blindness àVitamin A deficiency

5.     Pellagra à Niacin (Vitamin B2) deficiency

6.     Rickets à Vitamin D deficiency / calcium deficiency

7.     Beriberi à Vitamin B deficiency

8.     Anaemia àIron and copper deficiency


     

Food Tests










FOOD TESTS

TEST FOR REDUCING SUGARS

Reducing sugars include glucose and fructose. The test for reducing sugar are Benedict's tests and Fehling's test.

A.     BENEDICT'S TEST

·     Procedure

To 2cm3 of glucose solution in a test tube, add 2cm3 of Benedict's solution. Shake the mixture and heat it by immersing the test tube in a beaker of boiling water for 5 minutes.

·     Observation

Colour of benedict's solution (Copper(II)Sulphate) changes from blue to purple, then to brick red (Orange)

·     Inference

A reducing sugar present

N.B: You may carry out Benedict's test on either sugars e.g. maltose, lactose and fructose.




B. FEHLING'S TEST

·     Procedure

Add to 2cm3 of a solution of X of the mixtures of Fehling's solution. A and B. Shake the mixture and heat it by immersing the test tube in a beaker of boiling water for 3 minutes.

·     Observation

Colour of Fehling's solutions changes from green to orange (brick red)

·     Inference

X is a reducing sugar, e.g. glucose, fructose, lactose

TEST FOR NON-REDUCING SUGAR (E.G. SUCROSE)

A.     COMPLEX SUGAR TEST

·     Procedure

Boil the mixture of HCl and the non-reducing sugar. The acid hydrolysis, the non-reducing gar to a reducing sugar. Then the reducing sugar formed is treated with any of Benedict's solution and Fehling's solution.

·     Observation

The whole colour changes to orange (brick red)

·     Inference

Brick-red precipitate shows the presence of reducing in the hydrolysed solution, that is, sucrose or maltose present.

1.     TEST FOR STARCH

A.     IODINE TEST

·     Procedure

To solution, add few drop of iodine solution

·     Observation

The solution turns blue-black

·     Inference

The solution is a starch solution, i.e. starch present

NOTE: Starch foods like yam or potato can be used.

2.     PROTEIN TEST

A.     MILLION'S TEST

·     Procedure

To million's reagent add an equal volume of a protein solution (e.g. egg albumen) and boil for few minutes.

·     Observation

Brick-red precipitate is formed after boiling

·     Inference

Protein is present

B.     XANTHOPROTEIC TEST

·     Procedure

To a sample of proteinous food, add small amount (1cm3) of concentrated nitric acid (HNO3) and concentrated ammonium solution in excess (2cm3). Warm the mixture and then cool it.

·     Observation

The mixture turns violet or purple

·     Inference

Protein is present




TESTS FOR FATS AND OIL

A.     TRANSLUCENT TEST

·     Procedure

Rub a food substance containing fats against a white sheet of paper. Then place the paper in the path of propagation of light.

·     Observation

A translucent spot is observed on the paper.

·     Inference

Fat/Oil is present

B.     SUDAN III TEST

·     Procedure

Add a few drops of Sudan III solution to small quantity of oil or melted fats.

·     Observation

The solution turns red

·     Inference

Fat/Oil is present

C.     OSMIC TEST

·     Procedure

Add 1% osmic acid to a small quantity of fat or oil; and boil the mixture

·     Observation

The mixture turns black

·     Inference

Fat/oil is present

     

Digestive Systems









DIGESTIVE SYSTEM (HUMAN)

Digestion is the process of breaking sown complex food substances into smaller, simpler and absorbable units with the aid of enzymes. The human digestive system comprises the mouth, oesophagus, stomach, duodenum, small intestine, large intestine and anus.

·     Mouth: It consists of upper and lower jaws with teeth, sensitive tongue and ptyalin. Food passes through the oesophagus by peristalsis.

·     Stomach: It is guarded at the entrance by the cardiac sphincter. The food is churned after action of enzymes pepsin and renin on it, and then turns to chime. It is guarded at the end by the pyloric sphincter.

·     Duodenum: Food presence in the duodenum stimulates the pancreas to secrete pancreatic juice containing lipase. The liver also secretes the bile stored in the gall bladder.

·     Small intestine: It is a long coiled tube which provides a large surface area for digestion. The intestinal walls produce the invertase, erepsin and lipase.

·     Large intestine: It moves up in the right and falls at the left side. Faeces, which is gotten after water is absorbed is collected at the rectum.

·     Anus: This releases/ejects the wastes from the rectum.

Digestive Enzymes










DIGESTIVE ENZYMES

Enzymes are a globular protein which alters the rate of a biological chemical reaction but are not used up in the reaction.

Classes of Enzymes

The class to which enzyme belong, depends on the type of food upon which the enzyme acts. Based on this, enzymes are grouped into three (3) classes;

1.     Amylases

These enzymes act on Carbohydrates (starch and complex sugar) and change them to glucose (absorbable by the body). Example include: maltose, sucrose, lactose and ptyalin.

2.     Proteases

The enzymes act on proteins and break them down to absorbable amino acids.

Examples of proteases include pepsin, renin, trypsin and erepsin.

3.     Lipases

These enzymes break fats and oils to fatty acids and glycerol.

Examples of lipases include steapsin.

Characteristics of Enzymes

1.     Enzymes are proteinous in nature

2.     Enzymes are specific in their actions

3.     Enzymes are organic catalyst

4.     Enzymes are easily influenced by environment change

5.     Enzymes are required in small amount

6.     Enzymes act at specific pH

7.     Enzymes are sensitive to temperature. They function properly at optimum temperature.

     

Transport System











TRANSPORT SYSTEM

This refers to a group of organs or channels through which materials are moved between different parts of the body.

In simple unicellular organisms, diffusion is used as a medium of transport because the body is small and it has a large surface area to volume ration.

Media of Transportation

1.     Lymph in vertebrates

2.     Blood in multicellular animals

3.     Protoplasm in unicellular organisms

4.     Cell sap/latex in higher plants

5.     Body fluids in invertebrates

In plants, the following materials undergo or require transportation, water, mineral salts, oxygen, latex, hormones, carbon dioxide, excretory products, etc.

Plants use the following as mechanism for transportation

1.     Translocation; this occurs through the phloem tissues

2.     Cytoplasmic streaming: it is also known as cyclosis

3.     Conduction: this occurs through the xylem tissues

4.     Transpiration: it occurs through the stomata and lenticels

Animals make use of methods like protoplasm in unicellular organisms, body fluids in invertebrates, blood in multicellular animals, open transport system and closed transport system.

The Circulatory System

It comprises the blood, the blood vessels, lymph and the heart.

Blood is liquid tissue composed of various cells. They include.

1.     Erythrocytes/red blood cells (RBC)

2.     Leucocytes/white blood cells (WBC)

3.     Thrombocytes/Blood platelets

4.     Blood plasma

Diagram showing human circulatory system

Functions of Blood in Mammals

1.     It transports soluble organic compounds from the small intestine to other body parts.

2.     It transports oxygen from lungs to parts of the body.

3.     It transports carbon dioxide to the lungs and out of the body.

4.     It defends the body against foreign bodies and toxins.

5.     It distributes heat to maintain a constant body temperature

6.     It transports water and mineral salts.

7.     It transports hormones to target organs


Blood Vessels

They are channels that convey blood to various parts of the body. They include the arteries, veins and capillaries.

1.     Capillaries are narrowly tiny tubes that connect the veins and arteries.

2.     Arteries have the following features

·     They are situated deep in the body

·     They possess thick muscular walls

·     They carry blood away from the heart to other body parts

·     They carry blood under high pressure

·     They possess elastic walls

3.     Veins

Features

·     They are located near the skin surface

·     They possess thin less-muscular walls

·     They transport blood to the heart from body tissues

·     They carry blood under low pressure

·     They possess inelastic walls

·     They also possess valves

The Heart

It is a muscular pumping organ located in the chest region. It consists of four chambers; two upper chambers (auricles) and two lower chambers (ventricles). Blood enters the heart through two veins, namely; vena cavae and the pulmonary vein. Each pumping action of the heart is the 'heartbeat'.

There are two forms of blood circulation

1.     Pulmonary circulation: This is the circulation of deoxygenated blood from right ventricle to the lungs and return of the oxygenated blood through the pulmonary vein to left auricle of the heart. It is also known as 'lungs circulation.

2.     Systemic circulation: It is the movement of oxygenated blood from the heart to all body parts except the lungs through the aorta and then back to the heart.


Diagram showing the Human Heart


     

Respiratory System









RESPIRATORY SYSTEM

The organ through which oxygen is taken in and carbon dioxide is emitted is known as the 'respiratory organ'.

Respiratory Systems in Animals

Unicellular animals, hydra, earthworms and flatworms make use of their body surface for respiration. Insets use their tracheal system, spiders and scorpions use their lung books, fish , tadpoles and crustaceans use their skin and (mouth in some cases), and land vertebrates, birds and mammals use the lungs for respiration.

Breathing

It is the process by which organisms constantly change the fluid in contact with their respiratory surfaces in order to maintain stable oxygen rich air or water.

Mechanism of Breathing in Man

There are two (2) process involved;

1.     Inspiration/Inhalation

It is the process of taking air in through the nostrils into the lungs. During this process, the external intercostal muscles contract, the diaphragm contracts, volume of thoracic cavity increases, and air pressure decreases.

2.     Expiration/Exhalation

It is the process of removing stale air from the lungs. While this happens, the external intercostal muscles relax, the diaphragm relaxes, volume ofthoracic cavity decreases and air pressure is increased.


Mechanism of the Reparatory System in Man

The lungs, which are located in the thoracic are held together by intercostal muscles. The trachea which is held together by intercostal muscles. The trachea, which is divided into two bronchi, divides again severally to form the bronchioles which continue dividing until they become bubble-like air sacs called alveoli which are very close to the blood capillaries.

Carbondioxide diffuses from the blood into alveoli. The blood thus exchanged its carbondioxide for oxygen

Respiration in Plants

Plants lack special respiratory organs. Oxygen just diffuses in and out by some pores in the leaves known as the stomata and lenticels in the stem and breathing roots, leading to the intercellular spaces and mesophyll cells.


Diagram showing Human Respiratory system

     

Excretory System












EXCRETORY SYSTEM

It is the process by which metabolic wastes are disposed off from the body of living things.

Excretion is very useful in order to remove toxic metabolic wastes maintain water balance (osmoregulation) maintain water/salt balance(Homeostasis) and purify the blood of higher animals.

Excretory Organelles in Plants and Animals

1.     Protozoa excrete using the contractile vacuole

2.     Fishes excrete through their gills

3.     Flatworms excrete through their 'flame cells'. These are also known as 'Protonephridia'.

4.     Plants make use of stomata and lenticels for excretion

5.     Land vertebrates make use of kidney, skin, lungs and liver for excretion.

6.     Insects make use of their Malphigian tubules for excretion

Excretory Products in Plants

The kidneys are a pair of bean-shaped organs which are situated near the dorsal wall of the abdomen.

There are three main parts of the kidney, namely;

·     The cortex (a dark outer region)

·     Medulla (a light inner region)

·     Pelvis (funnel-shaped)

Formation of Urine

The formation of urine by the kidney is in two stages which are;

1.     Ultra-filtration: It is a process whereby the kidney's glomerulus filters out fluid from the blood. This filters fluid consists of glucose, are, slats, uric acid etc.

2.     Selective re-absorption: This is the absorption of useful materials into the body. The urine composes about 95% water, uric acid, urea and ammonia.

Functions of the Kidney

1.     It regulates the salt and water balance of the body (osmoregulation)

2.     It regulates the pH i.e. the salinity of the blood

3.     It excretes nitrogenous wastes, excess water and mineral salts in form of urine

Kidney Diseases

i.     Dropsy

ii.     Diuresis

iii.     Kidney stones

iv.     Nephritis

v.     Nephritis

vi.     Diabetes insipidus

Effects of Kidney Diseases

i.     Oedema: fluid retention and swelling of tissues

ii.     Alkalosis: excess alkaline in the body

iii.     Uraemia: retention of toxic wastes in the body

iv.     Acidosis: excess acid in the body

The Liver

It is a reddish-brown organ situated against the posterior surface of the diaphragm and partly covering the stomach. The hepatic portal vein directly connects the alimentary canal, releasing blood with high concentration of absorbed food particles.

Functions of Liver

1.     It is used to deaminate proteins in the body

2.     It also detoxifies the body of harmful chemicals

3.     It regulates the blood sugar

4.     It produces bile

5.     It also regulates the body temperature

6.     It stores iron and vitamins A and D

Diseases of the Liver

1.     Cancer of the liver

2.     Gall stones

3.     Cirrhosis of the liver

4.     Jaundice (also known as 'viral hepatitis')

The Mammalian Skin

This consists of two main layers which are the epidermis (outer layer) and the dermis (inner layer).

The epidermis is further sub-divided in three (3) namely;

i.     Cornified layer: It is the outermost dead layer which is composed dead cells.

ii.     Granular layer: It consists of living cells which gradually replace the cornified layer.

iii.     Malphighian layer: It consists of actively dividing living cells which replaces the granular and cornified layer gradually. In it is contained the 'melanin' which gives skin colour and also prevents the ultraviolet rays from piercing the skin. It also contains the 'keratin' which gives the skin its toughness.

In the dermis, there are hair follicles, blood capillaries, sweat glands, sebaceous glands, nerve endings, erector muscles and adipose tissue (subcutaneous fat) present since the dermis is regarded as the 'true skin'

Functions of the Skin

1.     It protects the tissues from damage

2.     It responds to stimuli in the environment

3.     It secretes sebumwhich contains metabolic wastes and also helps in regulating body temperature.

4.     It protects the skin against ultra-violet rays.

Care of the Mammalian Skin

1.     By bathing regularly bathing regularly with soap and water

2.     By prompt treatment of injuries by qualified medical personnel

3.     By exposing the skin to fresh air and moderate sunlight

4.     By protecting the skin from sharp objects

5.     By avoiding the sharing of towels and clothing materials with other people

6.     By applying oil or cream on the body regularly.

Homeostasis and Osmoregulation

Homeostasis can be explained as the maintenance of a stable internal environment irrespective of the conditions of the external environment while osmoregulation is the regulation of balance between the water and salt content of fluids in the body.

     

Tissues and Supporting Systems









TISSUES AND SUPPORTING SYSTEMS

Skeleton

It is the hard bony framework that gives support and structure to an organism.

Types

1.     Exoskeleton: The outer supporting tissue of the body which is made up of chitin. Examples of organisms with exoskeleton include crayfish, crab, snail etc.

2.     Endoskeleton: It is the inner supporting tissue of the body made up of bones and cartilage .It is found mostly in vertebrates .e.g. Man, Lion,etc.

3.      Hydrostatic Skeleton: It consists of body fluid which presses outwards against a muscular body wall. Example of animal possessing this is the earthworm

Functions of Mammalian Skeleton

1.     It provides support for the body

2.     It enhances breathing movement

3.     It produces blood cell in long bone marrows

4.     It provides a base for muscle attachment

5.     It provides rigidity and shape for the body

6.     It provides movement/locomotion

A detailed andlabelled diagram of the human skeletal system

The endoskeleton is further divided into two in mammals namely;

1.     Axial skeleton: Comprises of the skull, vertebral column, ribs, and sternum. The skull is made-up of cranium. (It houses the brain), the facial skeleton holds the nose, eyes and cheek and jaw muscles. The vertebrae is classified into five namely;

a.     Neck region/cervical vertebrae

b.     Thoracic region/Thoracic vertebrae

c.     Upper trunk region/Lumbar vertebrae

d.     Lower trunk region/ Sacral vertebrae

e.     Tail region/Candal vertebrae

Features of the Vertebrae

1.     Cervical vertebrae

a.     Atlas has; a highly reduced centrum, a large neural canal, broad transverse process.

b.     Axis has a prominent neural spine, broad and flat centrum, and large neural canal.

i.     It has relatively small centrum

ii.     It has large neural canal

iii.     It has a short neural spine

2.     Thoracic vertebrae

i.     It has a long neural spine

ii.     It has articular facts on the centrum

iii.     It has reduced transverse process

3.     Lumbar vertebrae

i.     It has large transverse process

ii.     It has thick centrum

iii.     It has a broad and massive neural spine

4.     Sacral vertebrae

i.     It has highly diminished neural canal

ii.     It's transverse process articulates with the pelvic girdle

iii.     The vertebrae are fused to form a solid mass of bone called sacrum

5.     Caudal vertebrae

i.     It is reduced to a mass of rectangular bone Centrum

ii.     It has no neural canal

The ribs, sternum and the thoracic vertebrae form the ribcage which protects the lungs and heart.

2.     Appendicular skeleton: It consists of thepectoral girdle, the pelvic girdle, the forelimbs and hind limbs. The girdle link the axial skeleton to the appendicular skeleton.

Features of Appendicular Skeleton

i.     Pectoral girdle consists of two halves each comprising a triangular bone (scapula shoulder blade) or the coracoid and clavicle (collar bone)

ii.     Pelvic girdle consists of two halves known as innominate bones. Each consists of three (3) fused bones; ilium, ischium, and pubis

iii.     Forelimbs is made up of one bone called the Humerus which is the nearest to the body, closely followed the radius and ulna (bones of the fore-arm)

iv.     Hind limbs consist of a single upper bone forming the thigh called femur and two bones of the lower leg called tibia and fibula. The small bones of the ankle are 'tarsals'

Joints

It is a point where two or more bones meet or articulate in the body. The bones are held together by a tissue called ligament.

Types of Joints

1.     Fixed or immovable joints

a.     Suture

b.     Fused joints

2.     Movable joints: they allow certain degree of movement

a.     Ball and socket joint permits movement in all planes. e.g. Hip and shoulder joints.

b.     Hinge joint permits movement in one plane only e.g. elbow, knee and finger joints.

c.     Sliding or gliding joint permits movement in two planes e.g. ankle and waist joint

d.     Pivot joint: It allows rotary movement e.g. in the neck between the atlas and axis.

Supporting Tissues in Plants

1.     Herbaceous plants; parenchyma cells, collenchyma cells, xylem tracheids and pericycle fibres

2.     Woody plants: sclerenchyma, xylem cells, pericycle fibres, and secondary growth thickening.

Functions

i.     They give rigidity/firmness to the plants body

ii.     They prevent breakage of stem

iii.     They confer resilience and flexibility to plants

iv.     They help to maintain the shape of plants


     

Sexual Reproduction











SEXUAL REPRODUCTION

It is a form of reproduction involving the fusion of male and female sex cells (gametes). Male gametes are called 'sperms' while female gametes are 'ova' or 'eggs'.

Male Reproductive Structure

The reproductive organs of the male are the testes which are located in the scrotal sac. It consists of seminiferous tubules which produce sperm. The epididymis leading to the sperm duct/ vas deferens stores the sperm and the vas deferens opens into the urethra passing through the centre of the penis. TheCowper'sand prostate gland also secretesome fluids which turns the sperm into seminal fluid/semen.

Female Reproductive Structure

The female reproductive organs comprise two ovaries. Each ovary is funnel-shaped at the oviduct/fallopian tube through which eggs pass when released. The womb/uterus is linked by oviducts and it leads to the outside through the vagina.

Diagram of male and female reproductive system

Gametes Structure

1.     Spermatozoa (sperm): It is a microscopic gamete of about 0.05mm long and has a pointed head containing the genetic material. It has a middle piece and a tail/flagellum for locomotion towards the egg.

2.     Ovum or egg:It is about 0.1mm in diameter and is immobile. It has a nucleus and cytoplasm, spherically surrounded by a plasma and vitelline membrane.

Development of New Organisms

The oviduct houses the fertilization process after which the fertilized egg/zygote passes through cell division repeatedly forming the embryo. This then gets the embedded in the soft endometrium of the uterus by a process known as 'implantation'.

Development of offspring starts after implantation. Nourishment is obtained through the villi from the uterine lining at the early stage but later on it uses the placenta as a transport organelle. The placenta is closely joined to the uterus lining and attached to the embryo by the tube called 'umbilical cord'.

Functions of Placenta

1.     It attaches the fetus to uterus wall

2.     It produces hormones to prevent ovulation and menstruation during pregnancy

3.     It absorbs digested food from mother's blood and transfers it to foetus.

4.     It allows for carbon dioxide exchange from foetus blood to oxygen from mother's blood

Functions of the Umbilical Cord

1.     It links the foetus to the placenta

2.     It holds the foetus in the amniotic cavity

Amniotic cavity/sac is filled with amniotic fluid which supports the developing baby throughout the pregnancy duration.

In man, gestation which is the period between conception and birth lasts for 36-40 weeks and is finalized with labor and delivery.


Reproduction in Insects

In insects, reproduction mostly involves metamorphosis which is the series of changes from fertilized egg to the adult stage. Metamorphosis in insects is divided in two (2).

1.     Complete Metamorphosis: This involves four stages i.e.

Egg → Larva →Pupa →Adult

Examples of insects in this category are; butterfly, beetles, housefly, bee, wasp, mosquito, etc.

2.     Incomplete Metamorphosis: It involves three stages i.e.

Egg →Nymph →Imago

Examples of insects in this category are; Aphids, termites, bugs, locust, grass hoppers, cockroaches, etc.

Courtship Behaviour in Animals

It is a complex behavioural pattern which is meant to entice the opposite sex, which may later evolve in mating. They are;

1.     Pairing

2.     Display e.g. Peacock and hen

3.     Territoriality

4.     Seasonal Migration

Reproduction in Flowering Plants

The reproductive organ of flowering plants is the flower which is made up of four (4) parts, namely;

Calyx (collection of sepals), Corolla (collection of petals), Androecium (male organ- Filaments and Anthers) and Gynoecium (female organ ovary style and stigma). The stamen is the general name for filaments and anthers while ovary, style and stigma are known collectively known as carpel/pistil.


Parts of a Flower

The parts of a flower include; pedicel/stalk, receptacle, petals, anther, style, ovary, ovules, stigma, pollen grains, filaments and sepals.

Placentation

This is the arrangement of ovary of a flower. The placenta is part of the ovary where the ovules are linked.

Types of Placentation

1.     Marginal placentation: ovules are linked to the placenta on only one ovary margin e.g. beans, flamboyant tree, etc.

2.     Parietal placentation: the ovules are attached to a synacopous ovary e.g. pawpaw.

3.     Basal: the ovules are arranged at the ovary base e.g. sunflower.

4.     Axile placentation: the carpels meet at the centre, forming one central placenta e.g. tomato, orange, okra, lily, etc.

5.     Free-central placentation: the ovules from the base of the ovary extend into one chamber of a synacarpous ovary e.g. coconut, prim rose, etc.

Some of the terms used in describing flowers include; Solitary flower, complete flower, incomplete flower, imperfect, perfect, pistillate, bisexual, stamiate, epigynous, hypogynous, perigynous flowers etc.

Pollination

This is the movement of pollen grains form the anther to the stigma of a flower by action of the wind or insects or other methods.

Agents of Pollination

1.     Insects, birds, and other animals

2.     Water

3.     Wind

4.     The plant itself.

Types of Pollination

1.     Self-pollination

2.     Cross pollination

Differences between Self and Cross Pollination

Fertilization in Flowering Plants

Self-PollinationCross Pollination
1It occurs only in bisexualIt occurs in both bisexual
2Only one parent is involved Two parents are involved
3No new varieties are formedThere is formation of new varieties
4HomogamyDichogamy

When a pollen grain lands on a stigma, it absorbs a sugary liquid which swells and germinates. A microscopic pollen tube is gotten from extine splits containing one nucleus which grows inside the style. The nucleus divides into two; while growing the larger tube nuclear and a smaller generative nucleus. The generative nucleus divides into two male nuclei. The pollen tube grows into the ovule passing through the micropyle and the end of it ruptures to give out two male nuclei inside the embryo sac. An embryo is formed when a nucleus fuses with the ovum, forming a zygote then later developing, while the second male nucleus fuses with the polar nucleus to form an endosperm nucleus (triploid cell) forming the endosperm.

The embryo differentiates into plumule (embryonic shoot), the radical (embryonic root) and sometimes the cotyledons. The following changes are noticed as the embryo develops;

i.     The stamen, calyx, corolla, stigma and style wither off

ii.     The polar nuclear nuclei becomes the endosperm

iii.     The ovule develop into seed

iv.     The integuments form the seed coat (testa)

v.     The ovary develops into fruit

vi.     The ovary will become the fruit wall (pericarp)

vii.     The antipodal or synergid cells disintegrate

Differences between a Seed and a Fruit

1.     A fruit shows the remains of a style while the seed does not

2.     The outer coat of a fruit is pericarp while that of a seed is testa

3.     Fruit has no micropyle while a seed has micropyle

4.     A fruit lacks endosperm while a seed has

5.     No embryo is present in a fruit while a seed contains an embryo

Fruits

A fruit is a developed ovary containing one or more seeds

·     True fruits: It is developed from only the ovary e.g. orange, etc.

·     False fruit: It is developed from other parts of the flower apart from the ovary e.g. cashew, apple, etc.

Types of Fruits

1.     Simple fruit: They are formed from a flower whose pistil is monocarpous e.g. legumes or, any carpels fused together e.g. tomatoes, maize, etc.

2.     Aggregate fruit: This is formed from one flower whose pistil is of several apocarpous e.g. apple, kolanut, etc. it is also known as compound fruits.

3.     Multiple fruit: It is a fruit formed from a bunch of flowers whose carpels are fused along with other floral parts. E.g. pineapple.

Types of Simple Fruits

1.     Succulent fruits; they are fruits whose pericarps are fleshy, e.g. berries, drupes, etc.

2.     Dry fruits: They are fruits whose fruit walls are dried when mature.

Dry dehiscent fruits are those whose pericarps have the ability to split in various ways to release their seeds. Dry indehiscent are those whosepericarp do not split at all.

Examples of dry dehiscent fruits include follicles (periwinkle and rubber), legumes (pride of Barbados, delonix), capsule (castor oil fruits, rubber, okra) and schizocarp (desmodium, cascia).

Examples of dry dehiscent fruits are achene (sunflower, buttercup), nut (corn, cashew nut), samara (African rosehood), caryposis (maize, millet), crypsela (tridax, emilia, aspilia etc.)

Dispersal of Fruits and Seeds

This is the scattering of fruit and seeds to different locations other than their parent plants location.

Advantages

1.     To introduce certain plants into new habitats.

2.     To prevent overcrowding

3.     To minimize disease spread

The agents of dispersal include the following, wind, water, animals including humans and self-explosive mechanism. Examples of fruits and seeds easily dispersed by wind are tridax, cotton, emilia, goat weed, etc. because they are light and are small in size.

Examples of fruits and seeds dispersed by animals include pepper, orange, mango, beans, etc. examples of fruit and seeds dispersed by water include coconut, water lily, lotus, etc.

Examples of fruit and seeds dispersed by self or explosive mechanism include oil bean seed, mahogany, pride of barbados, balson etc.

Dormancy of Seeds

It refers to a condition of very low metabolic rate and a period of reduced growth of the seed. Factors influencing dormancy of seeds include level of water content, coolness of water and impermeability to oxygen and water of their testa.

Germination of Seeds

This is the emergence of the embryo from the pericarp into a young plant. Certain conditions necessary for germination include water, oxygen, warmth, and viability of seed.

Types of Germination

1.     Hypogeal germination: A type of germination whereby the cotyledon remains in the soils, e.g. maize, rice coconut, etc.

2.     Epigeal germination: A type of germination in which the cotyledons are carried above the soil surface, e.g. beans, mango, groundnut etc.

Differences between Hypogeal andEpigeal

3Foliage leaves are the first photosynthetic tissueCotyledon is the first photosynthetic tissue

Coordination










CO-ORDINATION

This is brought about by the efficient working together of the endocrine (Hormonal) system and the nervous system of the body.

The Nervous System

It is composed of two parts namely; the Central Nervous System (CNS) and the Peripheral Nervous System (PNS). The CNS consists of the brain and the spinal cord while the PNS comprises the Autonomic and somatic systems.

The Brain

The brain is made up of brain cells, which are protected by the skull bone (Cranium). It is divided into three (3) main parts; the forebrain, mid brain and the hind brain.

1.     The Fore Brain

a.     The anterior part (for small detection)

b.     Cerebrum (or cerebral hemisphere)

i.     It coordinates and correlates impulses

ii.     It is the seat of intelligence, imagination

iii.     It is the centre of memory, reasoning and judgement

iv.     It controls voluntary actions or will power

c.     The posterior part (produces growth hormones and Anti-diuretic hormone ADH)

d.     The Hypothalamus

i.     It regulates water balance (osmoregulation

ii.     It controls blood pressure

iii.     It is the seat of anger and aggression

iv.     It controls speech, endocrine secretion, body temperature, sleep, alertness and body's urge for thirst and hunger

v.     It helps in homeostasis

vi.     It connects the pituitary gland to the thalamus.

2.     The Mid Brain

i.     It controls reflex movement of head, neck and trunk in response to visual and auditory stimuli.

3.     The Hind Brain

It consists of the cerebellum, pons and the medulla oblongata etc.

a.     The Cerebellum

i.     It is involved in posture and balance

ii.     It gets impulses from the ear

iii.     It also coordinates the voluntary muscles

b.     The Pons

i.     It is the link between the other parts of the brain, the cerebellum and the spinal cord.


c.     The Medulla Oblongata

i.     It controls the heartbeat

ii.     It regulates the saliva secretion

iii.     It controls breathing, digestion, blood circulation and involuntary actions like sneezing, blinking, yawning etc.

The Peripheral Nervous System (PNS)

It consists of all the nerves outside the brain and spinal cord linking the CNS to all parts of the body. It is divided into two;

1.     The Somatic Nervous System

It receives information/impulses from sensory receptors and transmits it to the CNS.

2.     The Autonomic Nervous System

It comprises sensory and motor nerves connecting the brain and spinal cord to internal organs. It is subdivided into two;

a.     Sympathetic system (prepares the body for action)

b.     Parasympathetic system (normalizes the body after stimulation by the sympathetic system)

The Neurone/Nerve Cell

It is a specialized cell that receives information and transmits it in form of impulses to the glands and muscles. It is the basic functional and structural unit of the nervous system.

It consists of three (3) major parts;

i.     Cell body

ii.     Dendrons

iii.     Axons: The slight gap between a neurone and another neuron is known as 'synapse'. The axon is covered by material known as the 'myelin sheath'


Types of Neurones

1.     Afferent or sensory Neurone: It conducts impulses from receptor or sensory organs to the CNS.

2.     Efferent or Motor Neurone: It relays impulses from the CNS to effector organs i.e. glands and muscles.

3.     Intermediate or Association Neurone: It relays and conducts impulses within the CNS.

Reflex Action

It is a quick and automatic response by an organ or the body to certain stimuli. E.g. sneezing, blinking, yawning etc. it is also known as involuntary action.

Reflex Arc

This is the nervous pathway that a reflex action takes. It comprises sensory cells, sensory neurone, intermediate neurone, motor neurone and the effectors.

A voluntary action is an action that is takes consciously in response to a certain stimulus.

The Endocrine System

The endocrine or hormonal system uses the hormones as a media for producing responses. A hormone is a chemical substance which is secreted in small quantities by the endocrine glands and carried to where they are needed in the blood stream, where it produces a response.

Types of Glands

1.     Thyroid Gland

It controls growth and body metabolism. It is located in the forebrain (neck region). It secretes a hormone known as Thyroxin (Growth Hormone)

·     Over secretion: hypothyroidism, gigantism

·     Under secretion: hypothyroidism, cretinism, dwarfism



2.     Pituitary Gland

It is also known as master gland. It is located in the fore brain and produces several hormones like anti-diuretic hormone (ADH), gonadotrophin, growth hormone and thyroid stimulating hormone.

3.     AdrenalGland

It is located on top of each kidney and secretes the adrenaline hormone (emergency hormone) which prepares the body for fight or flight.

·     Over secretion: hypertension, diabetes, over anxiety

·     Under secretion: fatigue, sluggishness and weakness.

4.     Pancreatic Gland

Also known as 'Islet of Langerhans', it is located between the stomach and the small intestine and it produces insulin which stimulates the liver to remove excess blood sugar.

·     Over secretion: low/reduced blood sugar

·     Under secretion: sugar diabetes/diabetes mellitus.

5.     Testes

It is situated in the groin and produces the testosterone (androgen) which influences the growth of male sex organs and secondary sex characteristics.

·     Over secretion: aggressive sexual urge

·     Under secretion: poor development of reproductive system, decline of male secondary sex characteristics.

6.     Ovaries

It is situated in the lower abdomen of females and it produces oestrogen which influences the development of female sex organs and secondary sex characteristics.

·     Over secretion: abnormal sex urge

·     Under secretion: poor reproductive system development and decline of female secondary sex characteristics.

Plant Hormones

1.     Auxins

i.     It is produced in the shoot and root apices

ii.     It promotes stem elongation

iii.     It causes apical dominance

iv.     It breaks seed dormancy

v.     It induces cell differentiation

2.     Gibberellins

i.     It is produced in embryos of germinating seeds and in roots

ii.     It affect the growth of roots and cell differentiation

iii.     It breaks dormancy in seeds and bulbs

3.     Abscissic Acid

i.     It is produced in leaves , stems, fruits and seeds of plants

ii.     It promotes dormancy in seeds

iii.     It inhibits growth in stem and roots

4.     Cytokinins (Kinins)

i.     It is produced in the roots of plants

ii.     It promotes growth of lateral buds

iii.     It delays senescence (ageing)

iv.     It affects root differentiation and growth

5.     Ethylene/Ethene

i.     It is produced in tissues of ripening fruits, stem nodes and flowers

ii.     It brakes bud dormancy

iii.     It also encourage ripening of fruits

Similarities between Nervous and Endocrine Systems

1.     They both stop acting once the action has been completed

2.     They both transmit impulses/ massages when stimuli is noticed

3.     Both provide communication means with the organisms body


Differences between Nervous and Endocrine Systems


Nervous Co-ordinationEndocrine Co-ordination
1It makes use of neurones/nerve cellsIt makes use of ductless glands
2Response to stimuli is fastResponse to stimuli is slow
3Present in animals onlyPresent in both plants and animals
4Messages are transmitted by electrical impulses along nervesMessages are carried by chemical messengers in the blood.

     

Sense Organs










SENSE ORGANS

An organ is a group of specialized tissues or receptors which receive stimuli and transmit the information to the nervous system e.g. nose, eye, tongue, ear and skin.

The Eye

It is the organ of sight and is situated in the orbit. The eyelashes prevent dust from entering the eyes.

The eye balls are of three layers which are the sclera, choroid and retina

1.     The Scelera

It is made up of tough, fibrous and whitish tissue that surrounds the eye externally.

Functions

i.     Protects the eye structures

ii.     It gives rise to the cornea

2.     The Choroid

It is the middle layer which is vascularised, pigmented and dark in colour


Functions

i.     It nourishes the eye cells

ii.     It removes excretory products

iii.     It prevents light reflection in the eyeball

3.     The Retina

It consists of two sensory cells: rods and cones. The cones are bright light sensitive while the rods are sensitive to dim light. The yellow spot has the highest concentration cells sensitive to light and it is where images are formed. The eyeball has two fluids filled chambers; aqueous humour and vitreous humour.

Accommodation is regarded as changing the lens thickness so as to focus both near and far objects.

Eye Defects

1.     Myopia/Short-sightedness: It is the ability of the eye to focus clearly on only near objects. It is caused by large or elongated eyeballs and can be corrected by wearing concave lensed glasses.

2.     Long-sightedness/Hypermetropia: This is when one can only see distant objects clearly. It is caused by small or short eyeballs and is connected by wearing convex-lensed glasses.

3.     Cataract: It is caused by bacteria. It is the opacity of lens which can later lead to blindness.

4.     Astigmatism: It is the unequal curvature of the eye. It mostly affects aged people and is corrected by wearing cylindrical shaped lenses.

5.     Conjunctivitis: It is the inflammation of the conjunctiva because of bacterial infection.

The Ear

It is the organ for hearing and balancing. It can be divided into three namely; the outer, inner and middle ear.

1.     Outer Ear: It is the external part of the ear near the eardrum. It includes the pins which navigates sound into the eardrum. The eardrum demarcates the outer from the middle ears.

2.     Middle Ear: It is an oval and air-filled cavity containing the malleus (hammer), incus (anvil) and stapes (stirrup), generally known as 'ossicles' which amplify sound.

3.     Inner ear: It contains the hearing and balancing organs enclosed in a bony case in the skull. The cochlea is a spiral tube with a fluid called 'perilymph' which produced impulses responding to sound waved. The semi-circular canals, being the organs of balance are filled with a fluid called 'endolymph'. Balance is the sense by which the brain detects the head position in order to coordinate the muscles to keep the body up right.


The Nose

It is the organ of smell. It has ciliated tips of olfactory cells on the surface of nasal cavities. Nervous impulses are interpreted by the brain as small sensations when they come from the olfactory nerve.

The Tongue

It is the taste organ. There are four main tastes which the taste buds are sensitive to; sweet, sour, bitter, salty. Taste buds for each taste are concentrated in various tongue areas.

Nervous impulses from taste buds are interpreted as taste.

The back sides, and tip of the tongue are sensitive to the bitter, sour and sweat and salty stimuli respectively.

The Skin

It has various receptors responding to environmental changes. They include; pacinian corpuscles, meisner's corpuscles pain receptors and temperature receptors.
